"""
MKT Context Commentary — Judges chapters 20–21
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-judges-20-21.py

Ch20: The civil war against Benjamin — Israel assembles at Mizpah, three battles,
      Gibeah destroyed (48 verses)
Ch21: Aftermath — oath crisis, Jabesh-Gilead destroyed, Shiloh virgins seized (25 verses)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "20": {
    "1": "<p>The assembly at <strong>Mizpah</strong> (<em>hammiṣpāh</em> H4709, 'watchtower/lookout') — the site is identified with Tel en-Naṣbeh, approximately 12 km north of Jerusalem in the territory of Benjamin. Mizpah was a recurring assembly point in pre-monarchic Israel: Samuel will later assemble Israel here (1 Sam 7:5-12; 10:17) and it will serve as Saul's mustering point. The assembly formula <em>kəʾîš ʾeḥāḏ</em> ('as one man') appears four times in Judges (6:16; 20:1,8,11) and is the standard idiom for unanimous tribal solidarity. <strong>Dan to Beersheba</strong> is the standard formula for the full north-south extent of Israel's settled land (ca. 240 km), with Gilead representing the Transjordanian tribes. The assembly of the entire nation for a judicial proceeding parallels ANE practices of national assemblies (<em>puhrum</em> in Akkadian sources) summoned to adjudicate matters of national significance.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>400,000 swordsmen</strong> — the census figure for the muster. ANE military censuses are common in royal inscriptions (Shalmaneser III records coalition forces at Qarqar in 853 BCE), and large coalition forces were feasible for major campaigns. Whether this figure is literal or conventional, the narrative's point is a massive response: nearly all of Israel's military capacity is mobilized against one tribe. The <strong>leaders of all the people</strong> (<em>pinnôt kol-hāʿām</em>) taking their stand reflects the formal structure of the tribal assembly: tribal chiefs and clan leaders as formal representatives, not merely a random gathering.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The Benjaminites <strong>heard</strong> of Israel's assembly — the reporting of the muster to Benjamin is not an ultimatum but intelligence reaching them through normal communication channels. Benjamin's geographic position is central: their territory lay between Ephraim and Judah, bordered the Jordan Valley to the east, and encompassed Jerusalem (though the city was not yet fully Israelite). Gibeah of Benjamin (identified with Tell el-Ful, 5 km north of Jerusalem) was the site of the crime. The Benjaminite question — 'How did this evil happen?' — is a formal legal inquiry (<em>ʾêk niqtāh hārāʿāh hazzōʾt</em>), the opening of a judicial proceeding.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Levite's account to the Mizpah assembly — he identifies himself as 'the husband of the murdered woman' and as a resident of the <strong>farthest part of the hill country of Ephraim</strong>. The phrase 'came to Gibeah of Benjamin' (<em>giḇʿatāh binyāmîn</em>) locates the crime in Benjamin's territory, which has legal significance: Benjamin bears communal responsibility for crimes occurring within their tribal allocation (Deut 21:1-9 establishes the principle of communal responsibility for an unresolved murder). The Levite's testimony is the formal accusation in the tribal legal proceeding.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Levite's account of the night attack — the <strong>lords of Gibeah</strong> (<em>baʿălê haggibʿāh</em>) surrounded the house and intended to kill him. He omits significant details from ch19 (the host's offer of his daughter; his own role in thrusting the concubine outside) — the account is self-serving. The phrase <em>lizkôt lî</em> ('intended to kill me') frames the crime as attempted murder of the Levite rather than the rape-murder of his concubine. ANE legal testimony in assembly proceedings was typically a plaintiff's narrative, not a sworn deposition — the listener was expected to ask follow-up questions.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Levite's action of cutting his concubine into <strong>twelve pieces</strong> and sending them throughout Israel's territory — this is the only narrative action described in his testimony that matches ch19. The gesture has ANE parallels: at Mari (18th century BCE), a dismembered donkey was sent through the territory to summon warriors to a muster (the 'donkey-killing' ritual for treaty obligations). The twelve pieces sent to all twelve tribal territories is a claim on the covenant solidarity of all Israel. The gesture bypasses normal judicial channels and makes an emotional-political appeal directly to the entire people.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Levite's closing appeal: <strong>'Here you are, all people of Israel; give your advice and counsel here'</strong> (<em>hinnēkem kūllākem bənê yiśrāʾēl hābû lākem dābār wāʿēṣāh pōh</em>). This is a formal call for communal deliberation — the assembly format requires a collective decision. The appeal invokes the covenant solidarity of 'all the people of Israel' as the relevant deliberating body. In ANE tribal assemblies, judicial decisions required communal consensus; Gideon's encounter with the Israelite tribes follows a similar pattern of appealing to national solidarity for a collective military-judicial response.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The unanimous response: <strong>'Not one of us shall go to his tent; not one of us shall return to his house'</strong> — the assembly invokes the ancient sacral war formula of commitment: no departure until the matter is resolved. <em>kəʾîš ʾeḥāḏ</em> ('as one man') — the solidarity formula repeated. The decision to wage war on Gibeah is framed as a sacred obligation analogous to holy war: the assembly has heard the testimony, identified the guilty party, and unanimously decided that Gibeah's crime requires national-level response. The tone is judicial-military: this is execution of communal justice, not personal revenge.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The assembly's military planning: <strong>casting lots</strong> (<em>nāʿal bigôrāl</em> H1486) to determine which units provision the army. The lot (<em>gôrāl</em>) was used throughout ancient Israel for decision-making (land allocation in Joshua; selection of Saul as king in 1 Sam 10; Jonah cast lots). The lot-casting here divides the assembly into two groups: fighters and provisioners. The logistics of a 400,000-man army required approximately 1/10th in supply roles — the one-in-ten ratio (10% provisioning, 90% combat) is historically plausible for a pre-industrial army on a short campaign.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The supply calculation: <strong>10 men per 100, 100 per 1,000, 1,000 per 10,000</strong> — a proportional levy system. The army provision plan targets <strong>Gibeah of Benjamin</strong> specifically — the campaign objective is not Benjamin as a whole but the specific city responsible for the crime. The provisioning structure suggests a professional military organization: detachments, proportional levy, and a named campaign objective. The purpose clause — 'to repay Gibeah of Benjamin for all the outrage that they have committed in Israel' — is a judicial declaration of the casus belli.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The mustering formula: <strong>'So all the men of Israel gathered against the city, united as one man'</strong> (<em>ʾîš ʾeḥāḏ ḥăḇērîm</em>). <em>ḥāḇēr</em> (H2270, joined/allied — the word implies a formal alliance, as in a confederacy) — the standard amphictyonic solidarity is invoked. Whether Israel had a formal amphictyony (twelve-tribe league centered on a central sanctuary, as proposed by Noth and others) is debated; but the narrative assumes a covenant-solidarity that binds all tribes to mutual defense and mutual justice. The assembly at Mizpah and the unanimous commitment exemplify this principle in its starkest form.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Israel sends messengers throughout <strong>all Benjamin</strong> demanding the surrender of the men of Gibeah. This is a formal ultimatum following the standard ANE pattern of demand-before-attack: military action was considered illegitimate unless preceded by a formal demand for redress. The messengers address all the tribe rather than just Gibeah, because the crime falls within Benjamin's tribal jurisdiction and Benjamin bears corporate responsibility for resolving it (Deut 21:2: the elders of the nearest city to an unresolved murder bear responsibility). Benjamin's refusal to surrender the men triggers the war.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The demand: <strong>deliver the worthless fellows</strong> (<em>bənê-bəliyyaʿal</em> H1100, sons of worthlessness/Belial) — the legal formula for persons who are morally outside the covenant community and subject to communal death (Deut 13:13-15: the formula for dealing with a city that has apostatized). Israel invokes the Deuteronomic purge formula: <em>ûbāʿartā rāʿ miyyiśrāʾēl</em> ('and you shall purge the evil from Israel') appears six times in Deuteronomy for capital crimes. Benjamin's <strong>refusal to listen</strong> to their brothers makes the tribe collectively guilty: they shield the perpetrators, making themselves accessories after the fact under ANE legal norms.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Benjamin <strong>musters from their cities</strong> to Gibeah — the tribe mobilizes for war rather than surrender. The Benjaminite muster is itself a signal that the tribe has chosen corporate solidarity with Gibeah over covenant justice with the rest of Israel. <strong>26,000 swordsmen plus 700 from Gibeah</strong> (vv15-16) — a tribal force of approximately 26,700 men opposing an Israelite force of 400,000. The military asymmetry is enormous, but the Benjaminites were known warriors (Gen 49:27: 'Benjamin is a ravenous wolf'). Saul (a Benjaminite) and his warriors will later demonstrate the tribe's martial capability.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>26,000 swordsmen plus the inhabitants of Gibeah</strong> — the dual count distinguishes between the general tribal levy and the specific Gibeah contingent that includes the men being sought. The Benjaminite muster is from 'their cities' (<em>mēʿārîm</em>) — suggesting a systematic mobilization of the entire tribe rather than just one city's forces. The tribal military capacity of Benjamin in this period is consistent with Genesis 49:27's characterization: a small but fierce tribe. That they muster despite being grossly outnumbered suggests either extreme tribal loyalty, calculation that YHWH would favor them, or underestimation of Israel's resolve.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The <strong>700 left-handed slingers</strong> from Gibeah (<em>šebaʿ-mēʾôt ʾîš bāḥûr ʾiṭṭēr yad-yəmînô</em>) — literally 'bound/restricted of right hand' — is a remarkable detail. The Benjaminites were known for left-handed warriors (Ehud in 3:15 is also a Benjaminite left-hander). The sling was one of the most effective ranged weapons of antiquity: Assyrian reliefs show professional slingers in battlefield formations, and range of 200+ meters with accuracy was achievable. 700 accurate slingers at a critical moment could inflict devastating casualties. The phrase 'every one could sling a stone at a hair and not miss' is a standard formula for elite proficiency.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Israel's total: <strong>400,000 swordsmen</strong> — the narrative restates the count to create contrast with Benjamin's 26,700. The ratio is approximately 15:1 in Israel's favor. Yet the first two battles result in devastating Israelite losses (22,000 in v21; 18,000 in v25), demonstrating that numerical superiority does not guarantee victory without YHWH's active participation. The narrative's theological point is that YHWH's delayed victory (granting Benjamin two improbable victories before the third battle) serves his larger purpose of both chastising Israel and ultimately fulfilling justice.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Israel's first consultation at <strong>Bethel</strong> (<em>bêt-ʾēl</em>) — the location of the ark of the covenant in this period (v27-28 confirms Phinehas ministered there). Bethel (identified with Beitin, 17 km north of Jerusalem) had been a major sanctuary since Jacob's vision (Gen 28:19). The consultation format — asking which tribe should go up first — parallels 1:1's opening consultation about conquering Canaan. YHWH's answer designates Judah, as in 1:2. The tribal lottery for who leads is the standard pre-battle consultation that maintains YHWH's sovereign direction of the campaign.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Israel sets out from their camp (<em>wayyāqām bənê yiśrāʾēl babbōqer</em>) — the dawn departure is the standard military timing for ancient battles: armies moved at first light to maximize daylight combat hours. <strong>Against Gibeah</strong> — the campaign target remains the specific city rather than Benjamin as a tribe. The deployment against a walled city in the hill country required specific tactics: the Benjaminite slingers (v16) would have been devastating to troops attempting to assault Gibeah's walls or approach positions.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Israel draws up for battle against Benjamin <strong>at Gibeah</strong>. The battle formation (<em>wayyaʿarəkû milḥāmāh</em> — the same verb as setting a table; 'arranging' a battle) implies a formal tactical deployment, not a charge. The approach to a fortified Benjaminite position would require infantry formations that could resist the elite Benjaminite slingers while maintaining cohesion. The terrain around Tell el-Ful (proposed Gibeah site) includes valleys and ridges that would have channeled approach routes and given defenders significant advantage.</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>22,000 Israelites fell</strong> on the first day — a catastrophic defeat for the numerically superior force. The loss of 22,000 from a 400,000-man army represents approximately 5.5% battlefield casualties, which would be devastating by ancient standards. First-day defeats against defending forces were common: the defenders knew the terrain, held elevated ground, and had prepared positions, while the attackers had to expose themselves approaching the fortified city. The shock of the defeat is the narrative's theological signal: YHWH has not guaranteed victory; the nation must purify itself before YHWH will act.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Israel <strong>encourages themselves</strong> (<em>wayyitḥazzēq ʿam yiśrāʾēl</em> — 'the people strengthened themselves') and resumes battle positions. <em>ḥāzaq</em> (H2388, to be strong/firm) is the standard encouragement vocabulary (Josh 1:6,7,9,18; Deut 31:6-7). The resumption of the battle formation in the same place as before suggests the army maintained discipline despite the first day's losses — the military-tribal organization held despite the defeat. The willingness to return to battle is itself notable: a single-day loss of 22,000 had demoralized many ancient armies into retreat.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The second consultation: Israel <strong>goes up and weeps before YHWH until evening</strong> — the pattern of seeking YHWH's guidance through lamentation before a second attempt. The question — <em>haʾôsîp lāḡešet lammilḥāmāh</em>, 'shall I again draw near to fight?' — is a formal oracle inquiry, not a rhetorical question. YHWH's answer: 'Go up against them' (<em>ʿălû ʾēlāyw</em>) — the same command as the first day, with no new tactical guidance. The consultation at Bethel is described as 'before YHWH' (<em>lipnê YHWH</em>), confirming the ark's presence there (explicitly stated in v27).</p>",
    "24": "<p>The second day's battle — Israel draws near against Benjamin. The <strong>three-battle structure</strong> of the campaign parallels other biblical battle sequences where YHWH delays full deliverance to teach dependence (cf. Gideon's three-stage confirmation process, ch6-7). The delay is not arbitrary: YHWH's purpose in allowing Israel to suffer defeat twice before granting victory is to prevent complacency about the outcome and to ensure that Israel approaches the battle with proper humility and dependence on YHWH's power rather than numerical superiority.</p>",
    "25": "<p><strong>18,000 more Israelites fell</strong> on the second day — again 'all these drew the sword' (<em>kullāh šōlĕpê ḥāreḇ</em>), suggesting the casualties were experienced frontline warriors. The cumulative loss is now 40,000 men in two days: approximately 10% of the total force. At this rate of attrition, even the numerically superior Israelite force would face serious strategic problems. The two consecutive defeats are a profound humiliation for a force of 400,000 that failed to subdue one city in two days. The theological message is unambiguous: numbers do not determine battles; YHWH does.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The third consultation at Bethel: <strong>all Israel, all the people, went up to Bethel, wept, sat before YHWH, and fasted until evening, and offered burnt offerings and peace offerings</strong>. The triple response — weeping, fasting, sacrifice — represents the full penitential repertoire of Israel's worship (cf. Joel 2:12-15). <strong>Burnt offerings</strong> (<em>ʿōlôt</em> H5930 — completely consumed on the altar, expressing total devotion) and <strong>peace offerings</strong> (<em>šəlāmîm</em> H8002 — shared between offerer and YHWH, expressing covenant fellowship) together make the complete sacrifice. The assembly's response to two defeats is not to retreat but to deepen their engagement with YHWH.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The ark of the covenant's location at Bethel is explicitly confirmed: <strong>the ark of the covenant of God was there in those days</strong>, and <strong>Phinehas son of Eleazar son of Aaron</strong> ministered before it. <strong>Phinehas</strong> (<em>pinḥās</em> H6372) was Aaron's grandson (Exod 6:25) and son of Eleazar who served as high priest after Aaron's death (Num 20:28). The Phinehas of Judges 20:28 must be either the original Phinehas (whose zeal earned him YHWH's covenant of peace, Num 25:10-13) or an early successor. Phinehas's intercession here echoes his previous atonement at Baal-Peor (Num 25:7-13; Ps 106:30-31).</p>",
    "28": "<p>Phinehas's oracle inquiry: <strong>'Shall I yet again go out to battle against Benjamin my brother, or shall I cease?'</strong> — the oracle question is phrased as a binary choice, as was standard in ANE divination. YHWH's unambiguous answer: <em>ʿălû kî māḥār ʾettennû bəyāḏekā</em> — 'Go up, for tomorrow I will give them into your hand.' The promise of deliverance is now explicit and time-specific: 'tomorrow.' The contrast with the previous two oracles (which gave no victory promise) signals that the condition for YHWH's active intervention has been met: Israel has sought YHWH with proper humility and sacrifice.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Israel sets an <strong>ambush around Gibeah</strong> (<em>mĕʾārəḇîm</em>) — the ambush tactic that YHWH instructed (v29, implied by v36 'the men of Israel gave ground to Benjamin because they trusted the ambush'). The ambush at Gibeah deliberately echoes Joshua's capture of Ai (Josh 8:2-22) where Israel used the identical strategy: feigned retreat drawing out the city's defenders, then ambush forces taking the undefended city. The deliberate allusion frames Israel's action as following the same military-theological pattern as Joshua's conquest.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The third day's deployment: <strong>as at other times</strong> — Israel sets battle formations exactly as on days one and two, presenting the same tactical scenario to draw out Benjamin's confidence. The repetition of the same deployment was intentional deception: Benjamin had defeated Israel twice using the same approach, so repeating it made the third day look like another frontal attack. The ambush forces are already in position (v36-37) — the third battle plan is a two-part operation requiring coordinated timing between the main force and the hidden ambush units.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Benjamin <strong>came out against the people and was drawn away from the city</strong> — the feigned-retreat tactic successfully lures the Benjaminite forces away from their defensive positions. The roads mentioned — toward Bethel, toward Gibeah, into the open country — describe the routes Benjamin used in their pursuit of the retreating Israelites. The initial Israelite casualties (approximately 30, <em>kəmippaʿam bəpaʿam</em>, 'as on previous occasions') in the third day's opening are intentional: they needed to appear convincingly as another Israelite defeat to maintain the deception long enough to spring the ambush.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Benjamin says: <strong>'They are routed before us as before'</strong> — their confidence in repeating the previous victories is the deception's success. Israel's ordered retreat while sustaining controlled casualties is itself a military achievement: maintaining cohesion while withdrawing under pursuit is extremely difficult. The mention of 'drawing them away from the city' confirms that the ambush tactic's first objective — separating the defenders from their fortifications — has succeeded. An ancient fortification without its garrison was nearly helpless against a determined attacker.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The battle reaches <strong>Baal-tamar</strong> (<em>baʿal tāmār</em> H1193, 'lord of the palm tree' — an unidentified site near Gibeah) — the main Israelite force turns and makes a stand. Simultaneously, <strong>the men of Israel who were in ambush rushed out of their place from Maareh-geba</strong> (<em>mîmaʿărēh-geḇaʿ</em>). The timing of the ambush's emergence is the critical moment: too early and Benjamin would flee back to Gibeah; too late and the main force could be broken. Ancient military coordination without radio communication depended on pre-arranged signals (smoke, flags, trumpets) or time-based triggers.</p>",
    "34": "<p><strong>10,000 chosen men of Israel</strong> came against Gibeah — the ambush force is specified as elite warriors (<em>bāḥûr</em> H977, chosen/selected — the same term used for the elite Benjaminite slingers in v16). The battle was severe (<em>wəhammilḥāmāh kāḇəḏāh</em> — 'the battle was heavy/severe'). <strong>They did not know that disaster was close</strong> (<em>lōʾ yāḏəʿû kî-naggaʿat ʿălêhem hārāʿāh</em>) — the Benjaminites outside the city pursuing the retreating main force do not yet realize their city is under attack from behind. The phrase 'did not know' is an ironic reversal of the Levite's concubine narrative: the perpetrators now face an unseen evil approaching them.</p>",
    "35": "<p>YHWH's decisive intervention: <strong>YHWH defeated Benjamin before Israel</strong> — the theological summary precedes the tactical narrative that follows. The casualty figure: <strong>25,100 drawn-sword men of Benjamin</strong> fell on this day. Benjamin's total force was approximately 26,700 (v15-16); losing 25,100 in a single day means over 93% of the Benjaminite army was destroyed. The juxtaposition with v21 (22,000 Israelites) and v25 (18,000 Israelites) is intentional: YHWH allowed Israel to suffer 40,000 casualties over two days, then destroyed 25,100 Benjaminites in one.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The Israelites 'gave ground to Benjamin' (<em>wayyittənû bənê yiśrāʾēl mākôm libinyāmîn</em>) — the narrator reveals that the retreat was deliberate. <em>bāṭaḥ</em> (H982, trusted/relied on) — they relied on the ambush (<em>hāʾōrēb</em>). The tactical picture is now clarified retrospectively: the two-day withdrawal that appeared to be defeat was intentional maneuvering. The three-part structure — strategic retreat, surprise flank attack, burning of Gibeah — is militarily coherent and parallels Joshua's Ai campaign precisely.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The ambush forces <strong>rushed against Gibeah</strong> (<em>wayyāšêṭ hāʾōrēb wayyabôʾ ʾel-giḇʿāh</em>) — the sudden advance on the undefended city. <em>šāṭaṭ</em> (H7786, to rush/stretch out suddenly — a rare verb suggesting rapid movement) followed immediately by <strong>put all the city to the sword</strong> (<em>wayyak ʾet-kol-hāʿîr lepî-ḥāreḇ</em>). The speed of the city's capture confirms that Gibeah's garrison had been drawn out entirely by the three-day battle sequence: no resistance is described at the walls. The city walls that had protected the perpetrators are now empty.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The pre-arranged signal: <strong>a great cloud of smoke rising from the city</strong> (<em>maśʾēt heʿāšān</em> H4864 H6227). Smoke signals were standard military communication in antiquity: Joshua 8:20 uses the same signal (smoke from burning Ai) to coordinate the ambush's counterattack. Pre-arranged smoke signals required clear sightlines and pre-agreed meanings, suggesting a level of battlefield coordination between units separated by several kilometers. The smoke signal triggers the main force's turn-and-fight response simultaneously with the Benjaminites' realization of what has happened.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The main Israelite force <strong>turns in the battle</strong> — the feigned retreat reverses direction when the signal appears. Benjamin's confidence at this moment is at its maximum: they believe they are again routing Israel (v32). The turn is a shock: troops in pursuit suddenly face a formed enemy line turning to engage, while simultaneously seeing their city in flames. The psychological collapse of the pursuing force when they realize their city is burning behind them is a standard result of this ambush-and-fire tactic: it eliminates both the tactical and the psychological security of the defending force.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The smoke pillar rises from Gibeah — the city is <strong>going up in its entirety to the sky</strong> (<em>ʿāśān haʿîr ʿālāh haššāmayim</em>). The total destruction of Gibeah by fire is the application of the Deuteronomic <em>ḥērem</em> (ban) on a city whose inhabitants have committed the crime of Genesis 19 (Sodom-equivalence). The comparison of Gibeah's fate to Sodom is explicit in the narrative's allusions (19:22 — 'sons of Belial' besieging the house; Lot-like host offering daughters). The fire that destroyed Sodom now consumes Gibeah.</p>",
    "41": "<p>The Benjaminites' terror: <strong>Benjamin saw that disaster had struck them</strong> (<em>wayyərʾû bənê-binyāmîn kî nəgûpāh hîʾ lāhem</em>). <em>nāgap</em> (H5062, to strike/smite — used of plagues and military defeats sent by YHWH) — they recognize YHWH's judgment. The terror (<em>ḥārēḏ</em> H2729) is the same word as 'Harod' (the Spring of Trembling where Gideon's army drank). The Israelite main force, now turning to fight rather than flee, combined with the rising smoke from Gibeah, produces an instantaneous psychological collapse in the Benjaminite pursuit force.</p>",
    "42": "<p>Benjamin flees <strong>toward the wilderness road</strong> (<em>derek hammiḏbār</em>) — the open desert to the east, toward the Jordan Valley. Wilderness flight was the standard escape route from battle in the central hill country: the terrain was unfamiliar to pursuers but offered concealment to fugitives. The battle catches up with them: <strong>the men from the cities were destroying them in the midst of them</strong> — the ambush forces emerging from Gibeah cut off the retreat from behind while the main Israelite force pressed from in front. The classical 'hammer and anvil' tactical encirclement.</p>",
    "43": "<p>The Israelites <strong>encircled Benjamin, pursued and easily trodden them down from Nohah to opposite Gibeah on the east</strong>. <strong>Nohah</strong> (<em>nôḥāh</em>) is a site not otherwise identified. The encirclement phrase (<em>kitrû ʾet-binyāmîn hirḏîpû mənûḥāh</em>) uses the vocabulary of surrounding (<em>kātar</em> H3803, to encircle/surround) combined with pursuit (<em>rāḏap</em> H7291). The tactical description is a complete annihilation: encirclement, pursuit, and no avenue of escape. The specificity of 'opposite Gibeah on the east' identifies the killing ground geographically — where the retreating Benjaminites were caught between the burning city and the pursuing Israelite force.</p>",
    "44": "<p><strong>18,000 men of Benjamin fell</strong> in this phase of the battle — the initial phase of the rout. This is less than the 25,100 total (v35) and represents the first stage of casualties as the Benjaminite force disintegrated. The number 18,000 also matches the Israelite casualty figure on the second day (v25) — whether this parallel is intentional is debated. The battle's third day produces Benjaminite casualties nearly matching Israel's total losses over the first two days, demonstrating the reversal of fortunes.</p>",
    "45": "<p>The surviving Benjaminites flee to the <strong>wilderness toward the rock of Rimmon</strong> (<em>ṣûr-rimmôn</em> H7417) — identified with Rammun, a prominent rocky summit approximately 9 km east of Bethel, 600 meters above the surrounding terrain. The rock of Rimmon provided a natural fortress: steep approach, limited access routes, and visibility over the surrounding desert. <strong>5,000 more fell on the Gidom roads</strong>, and <strong>2,000 were cut down near Gidom</strong> — the pursuit casualties continue during the flight. The successive casualty figures (18,000 in v44; 5,000 + 2,000 = 7,100 in v45) total 25,100, matching v35's summary figure.</p>",
    "46": "<p>Summary of Benjamin's casualties: <strong>25,000 drawn-sword men</strong> fell that day, all warriors. The summary restates v35's figure (25,100, with slight rounding). The complete destruction of Benjamin's military forces means that the 600 survivors at Rimmon (v47) represent the entire surviving male population of fighting age in the tribe. Benjamin has been reduced from one of Israel's tribes to a remnant of 600 men — a demographic catastrophe that ch21 will struggle to address.</p>",
    "47": "<p><strong>600 men turned and fled to the wilderness toward the rock of Rimmon</strong> and remained there <strong>four months</strong>. The four-month stay at Rimmon suggests they were waiting for Israel's anger to subside enough to negotiate safe passage. The rock of Rimmon as a refuge provided natural defensibility against any Israelite follow-up campaign: 600 determined defenders on a rocky summit could hold against a much larger force. The four months also gave time for the national grief and oath-crisis to develop (ch21) that would eventually motivate efforts to restore rather than exterminate Benjamin.</p>",
    "48": "<p>Israel's total destruction of Benjamin: <strong>all the cities they found, they put to the sword</strong> and burned every city (<em>ʾēt-kol-hāʿîr ʾăšer māṣāʾû šillĕḥû bəʾēš</em>). The campaign against Benjamin's cities is the application of the <em>ḥērem</em> formula (Deut 13:15-16: for an Israelite city that has apostatized, 'you shall put its inhabitants to the sword... burn the city with all its spoil'). The complete burning of all Benjaminite cities except Gibeah (already burned) represents the maximum possible covenant judgment applied to a tribe. Benjamin's entire settled infrastructure is destroyed; only the 600 at Rimmon survive.</p>"
  },
  "21": {
    "1": "<p>The oath at Mizpah: <strong>'None of us shall give his daughter in marriage to Benjamin'</strong> (<em>lōʾ-yittēn ʾîš mibbanôtāyw ləḇinyāmîn ləʾiššāh</em>). The oath was sworn during the original assembly at Mizpah before the battles, presumably as a punitive measure to isolate Benjamin socially after the war. Marriage alliances were the primary mechanism of political and social integration between Israelite tribal units — cutting Benjamin off from marriage connections meant cutting them off from the covenant social network. The oath, once sworn, was binding under ANE covenant law: breaking it incurred divine sanction.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The people come to <strong>Bethel, sit there before God until evening, and lift up their voices and weep bitterly</strong> — the formal lamentation posture for communal grief (cf. 20:23,26: the same actions before the second and third battles). <em>ʾădōnāy YHWH ʾĕlōhê yiśrāʾēl</em> (Lord YHWH, God of Israel) — the formal appellative used in solemn address to the covenant deity. The assembled community grieves the consequence of their own military success: they have nearly destroyed a tribe of Israel, and the oath they swore has made that destruction permanent.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The lament: <strong>'Why, O YHWH, God of Israel, has this happened in Israel, that today one tribe should be lacking from Israel?'</strong> (<em>lāmmāh YHWH ʾĕlōhê yiśrāʾēl hāytāh zōʾt bəyiśrāʾēl</em>). The theological assumption behind the lament is that the twelve-tribe structure of Israel belongs to YHWH's covenant promises — no tribe can simply be eliminated without disrupting the covenant order. The number twelve has symbolic-theological weight: twelve sons of Jacob, twelve tribes, twelve months, twelve stones (Joshua's memorial). The loss of a tribe is not merely demographic but covenantally destabilizing.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The assembly builds an <strong>altar and offers burnt offerings and peace offerings</strong> (<em>wayyibənû šām mizbēaḥ wayyaʿălû ʿōlôt ûšəlāmîm</em>) — the same combination as 20:26, the penitential sacrifice before the victorious battle. The building of a new altar at Bethel alongside the existing sanctuary may reflect the extraordinary circumstances: the national assembly constructing its own altar in the crisis. The sacrifices express both consecration (burnt offerings) and covenant fellowship (peace offerings) — the community is seeking renewed YHWH-relationship in the aftermath of the catastrophe they helped create.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The second oath: <strong>'What one of the tribes of Israel did not come up to YHWH at Mizpah?'</strong> — this oath called for death against any tribe that failed to participate in the muster. The demand for universal tribal participation in national judicial-military actions was based on covenant solidarity obligations. The application of the death penalty to non-participants reflects the amphictyonic principle: refusal to stand with the covenant community when called was itself a covenant violation (cf. the curse against Meroz in 5:23 for not helping YHWH against Sisera). The oath creates a second instrument for Israel's crisis.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Israel <strong>grieved for Benjamin their brother</strong> (<em>wayyinnāḥămû bənê yiśrāʾēl ʾel-binyāmîn ʾāḥîw</em>) — the term <em>ʾāḥ</em> (H251, brother) is the covenant-kinship term. <em>nāḥam</em> (H5162, to be sorry/repent/grieve — the same root as Noah's naming in Gen 5:29 and YHWH's 'repenting' over human evil in Gen 6:6) — the community experiences genuine grief over what their punitive action has produced. The grief is for a fellow Israelite, expressed in the language of brotherly solidarity that had been absent during the war. The emotional reversal — from military zeal to brotherly grief — sets up the complex moral situation of ch21.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The oath problem: <strong>'What shall we do for wives for those who are left, since we have sworn by YHWH that we will not give them any of our daughters as wives?'</strong> The oath has created a dilemma: they want to preserve Benjamin, but their binding oath prevents them from giving daughters directly. ANE legal traditions recognized that binding oaths created obligations that could not simply be set aside, but that creative solutions might satisfy the letter of the oath while achieving the desired result. The chapter explores two such solutions: both are ethically troubling, suggesting that the narrator views the entire episode as a consequence of rash oath-swearing.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The investigation of <strong>Jabesh-Gilead</strong>'s absence from the Mizpah muster — the city is identified with Tell Abu Kharaz in the Jabbok Valley, Transjordan (alternative: Tell el-Maqlub). Jabesh-Gilead will appear again prominently in connection with Saul (1 Sam 11: Saul rescues Jabesh from Nahash; 31:11-13: Jabesh-Gilead's men retrieve Saul's body). The connection between Benjamin and Jabesh-Gilead established here is the basis for Jabesh's loyalty to Saul's house throughout the monarchy period. The absence of Jabesh from the muster is verified by census: <em>ûpāqad hāʿām</em> (H6485, mustering/numbering/inspecting — the same verb as 'visiting' and 'appointing').</p>",
    "9": "<p>The census confirms: <strong>no one from Jabesh-Gilead was present</strong> (<em>wəhinnēh ʾên-šām mêyōšēḇ giḇʿāh</em> — 'and behold, there was no one from the inhabitants of Jabesh-gilead'). The census at Mizpah was a tribal muster-roll: each tribal unit was accounted for, enabling identification of absent communities. The absence of Jabesh-Gilead provides the assembly with both a crisis solution (virgin girls of Jabesh as potential wives for Benjamin) and a punitive justification (the oath of death against non-participants).</p>",
    "10": "<p>Israel sends <strong>12,000 warriors to Jabesh-Gilead</strong> with explicit instructions: kill every male, every woman who has known a man, but save virgin women. The force of 12,000 represents a significant detachment — 3% of the original 400,000 — suggesting a serious military operation rather than a punitive raid. The military commission against a fellow Israelite town applies the <em>ḥērem</em> formula (kill all non-virgins) that was just applied to Benjamin's cities. The logical and moral consistency of the assembly is coherent within its own framework but deeply troubling: one group nearly destroyed; another destroyed to save the first.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The specific instruction: <strong>destroy every male and every woman who has known a man</strong> (<em>ʾeḵ hāʾiššāh yāḏəʿāh miškaḇ zākār taḥărîmû</em>). The sexual-knowledge criterion for execution follows the same logic as the original crime investigation: sexual purity of women as a criterion for sparing or killing. The legal basis for distinguishing virgins from non-virgins in this military-demographic context (as wives for Benjamin) has no explicit Torah parallel — the assembly is improvising a solution from available legal-cultural resources. The women of Jabesh-Gilead become pawns in a crisis created by the men's rash oaths.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>400 virgin girls</strong> were found among the inhabitants of Jabesh-Gilead. The population mathematics: Benjamin had 600 survivors (20:47); 400 Jabesh women falls 200 short. The deficiency sets up the Shiloh episode (vv19-22). The women are brought to <strong>the camp at Shiloh in the land of Canaan</strong> — Shiloh (Khirbet Seilun, 35 km north of Jerusalem) was the location of the tabernacle/ark in this period (Josh 18:1; 1 Sam 1-4). The assembly at Shiloh marks the transfer from the war's Mizpah-Bethel axis to the central sanctuary.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Israel sends a <strong>peace offer to Benjamin at the rock of Rimmon</strong> (<em>šālom</em> H7965 — the formal offer of peace ending hostilities, the ANE counterpart to a treaty or armistice). The 600 Benjaminites at Rimmon have been in the wilderness for four months (20:47). The peace offer presumably includes assurances of safety and the proposed solution to the wife-shortage. <strong>Rimmon to Shiloh</strong> involves a journey of approximately 20 km — Benjamin coming out of their wilderness refuge to the central sanctuary marks the formal end of the civil war and the beginning of restoration.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Benjamin returns, and the <strong>400 Jabesh-Gilead women</strong> are given to them. The 200 remaining without wives means the solution is still incomplete — prompting the Shiloh plan. The giving of women as war prizes/captives was standard ANE military practice: Deut 21:10-14 regulates the marriage of captured women, requiring a month's mourning period before marriage. The narrative does not comment on whether this requirement was followed, but the provision exists in Torah. The women of Jabesh-Gilead are technically captives of the Israelite army, given to Benjamin as wives — a second-generation application of the Deuteronomic captive-wife provision.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>The people had compassion on Benjamin</strong> (<em>wayyinnāḥămû hāʿām ləḇinyāmîn</em>) — the same root as v6 (<em>nāḥam</em>), expressing grief-generated desire to restore. <em>pereṣ</em> (H6556, breach/rupture/gap — the word used for Achan's sin creating a 'breach' in Num 25:9's Perez-Uzzah) — YHWH has made a breach in the tribes. The attribution of the breach to YHWH (<em>ʾăšer-ʿāśāh YHWH pereṣ bəšiḇṭê yiśrāʾēl</em>) is the theological interpretation: the civil war's destruction of Benjamin was YHWH's judgment on the tribe, not merely Israel's military success. YHWH's agency in the breach is the premise for seeking YHWH's restoration.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The elders' problem: <strong>how shall we provide wives for those remaining since the women of Benjamin have been destroyed?</strong> The Benjaminite women were all killed in the war (20:48: 'all the cities they came to, they put to the sword'). The 400 Jabesh women filled some slots, but 200 men remain without wives. The elders are the deliberative body responsible for the solution — the same tribal-elder structure that failed to enforce covenant justice in the first place must now exercise creative problem-solving to reverse the demographic catastrophe that their collective decisions produced.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The elders' declaration: <strong>'There must be an inheritance for the survivors of Benjamin'</strong> (<em>yərūšat pəlêṭāh ləḇinyāmîn</em>). <em>yərūšāh</em> (H3425, inheritance/possession — the covenant term for tribal territorial allotment, Josh 12:6-7) — the tribal inheritance cannot continue without descendants. <em>pəlêṭāh</em> (H6413, remnant/those who escape/survived) — the remnant theology: even after judgment, YHWH preserves a remnant to continue the covenant line. The elders' legal and theological reasoning is correct: the dissolution of a tribe would violate the covenant structure. The problem is that their two oaths (no daughters; death to non-participants) block the obvious solution.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The first oath's binding force: <strong>'We cannot give them wives from our daughters'</strong> because of the sworn oath (<em>ʾănaḥnû lōʾ-nûkal lātēt lāhem nāšîm mibbanôtênû kî-ḥilû bənê-yiśrāʾēl lēʾmōr</em>). ANE oath law (including biblical law) treated sworn oaths as binding even if their consequences were severe (cf. Jephthah's daughter in ch11). The impossibility of directly giving daughters is what forces the assembly to seek the indirect solution of the Shiloh festival. The narrative implicitly criticizes the rash oath-swearing: the same people who swore this oath now must engineer a legal workaround to avoid the consequences.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The Shiloh solution: <strong>an annual feast of YHWH at Shiloh</strong> (<em>ḥag YHWH bəšilōh miyyāmîm yāmîmāh</em> — 'a feast of YHWH at Shiloh from year to year'). The annual feast (<em>ḥag</em> H2282 — a pilgrimage festival involving dancing and celebration) at Shiloh is attested in 1 Sam 1:3 (Elkanah's annual pilgrimage) and 1 Sam 1:21. The festival involved dancing in the vineyards — a harvest celebration combining religious observance with communal festivity. <strong>North of Bethel, east of the highway, south of Lebonah</strong> — the geographical triangulation locates Shiloh precisely for travelers coming from multiple directions.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The instruction to the 200 Benjaminites: <strong>lie in wait in the vineyards and watch</strong> (<em>ʾirəbû bakkaramîm</em>). <em>ʾāraḇ</em> (H693, to lie in wait/ambush) — the same word used for the ambush at Gibeah (20:29,33) and the military ambush at Ai (Josh 8:4). The application of ambush vocabulary to wife-seizure is jarring: it frames the capture of women at a religious festival using the same military-tactical language as the civil war. The narrative does not endorse the action — it reports it. The women who are 'seized' are described as the daughters of Shiloh dancing in the festival, not as war captives.</p>",
    "21": "<p>When the daughters of Shiloh come out to dance, Benjamin should <strong>each seize a wife for himself from the daughters of Shiloh and go to the land of Benjamin</strong>. The festival dance in the vineyards was likely a harvest celebration associated with the grape harvest (cf. Isa 16:10; Jer 48:33 for vineyard celebrations). The dancing was public and participated in by unmarried young women. That Benjamin is instructed to 'seize' (<em>waḥăṭaptem</em> H2414, to snatch/seize) — not court, negotiate, or pay bride-price — reflects the extremity of the situation: the normal marriage protocols (negotiation, bride-price, parental consent) are being deliberately bypassed to avoid triggering the oath.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The anticipated complaint management: <strong>if their fathers or brothers come to complain, say: 'Grant them graciously to us, because we did not take a wife for each man in battle; for you did not give them to us; otherwise you would now be guilty'</strong>. The legal argument is tortured: the fathers did not 'give' the daughters (which would violate the oath), so they are not oath-breakers; the daughters were 'taken' without the fathers' explicit consent. The argument's weakness is its own evidence that the assembly knows this is ethically problematic. The instruction to manage complaints rather than prevent them suggests awareness that the scheme is morally borderline.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Benjamin does as instructed: <strong>each took his wife from the dancers, and they went and returned to their inheritance</strong> (<em>wayyišəbû ʾel-naḥălātām</em>). The return to their tribal <em>naḥălāh</em> (inheritance/allotment) is the covenantal goal: Benjamin as a tribe with territory and descendants can perpetuate itself. <strong>Rebuilt the cities and settled there</strong> (<em>wayyibənû ʾet-hāʿārîm wayyēšəbû bāhem</em>) — Benjamin begins reconstructing their devastated tribal infrastructure. The rebuilding of Benjaminite cities is the first constructive act since the war began in ch19; it signals the resumption of covenant normalcy even in the aftermath of catastrophe.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Israel departs, <strong>every man to his tribe and to his clan</strong> (<em>ʾîš ləšiḇṭô ûləmišpaḥtô</em>) — the dispersal formula for the end of a national assembly. The tribal-clan structure reasserts itself after the exceptional national gathering. The departure from Shiloh back to tribal territories is the final act of the Judges narrative before its closing verdict. The twelve-tribe structure is nominally intact: Benjamin, even devastated and rebuilt with seized wives, remains a tribe with territory and heirs. The covenant structure survives, barely — but what has been preserved is a severely damaged version of what YHWH's covenant community was meant to be.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The closing verdict: <strong>'In those days there was no king in Israel. Everyone did what was right in his own eyes'</strong> (<em>bayyāmîm hāhēm ʾên meleḵ bəyiśrāʾēl ʾîš hayyāšār bəʿênāyw yaʿăśeh</em>). The refrain (17:6; 18:1; 19:1; 21:25) reaches its final and most resonant occurrence here, after the book's darkest episodes: private idolatry (Micah's shrine), tribal theft (Dan's theft of Micah's priest), sexual violence and murder (Gibeah), civil war (chs20-21), and the capture of women at a religious festival. The final verdict interprets all of it through the lens of kinglessness: without a human king enforcing the Deuteronomic covenant, every person (and tribe) becomes their own moral authority — with catastrophic results. The book ends as a long argument for the monarchy, specifically for a king after YHWH's own heart.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'judges')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'judges', c)
    print(f'judges mkt-context: wrote {sum(len(v) for v in CONTEXT.values())} verses across ch 20-21')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
